    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>N.Y.</placeName>
                <date>Sunday</date>, The</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>2nd of Tammuz</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><date>(June) 1866</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <add>צ"ה ניוארק אור ליום ב' תמוז ברכת ד' לפ"ע</add>
            </p>
            <p>Greetings, etc. to my<lb/> friend, etc. <persName>Isaac</persName> son of
                    <persName>Uri Leeser</persName>:</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">After my greetings of peace, I want<lb/> to ask you for one favor,
                and I am<lb/> ready to pay for your trouble, as<lb/> much as you will justly impose
                upon<lb/> me. God is my witness that it is not<lb/> for my own glory but for Him and
                his<lb/> Torah that I do this. There is a time<lb/> for silence and a time for
                speech.<lb/> We should not permit The final mish-<lb/>nah of Chapter IX of the
                Treatise Sotah<lb/> to come true, “The wisdom of the Scribes<lb/> grows stale, and
                the righteous become<lb/> despised, then truth is lacking.”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It is now three days since an old<lb/> man died here and departed
                this life<lb/> from us and all <placeName>Israel</placeName>. His name was<lb/>
                <persName>Rabbi Isaac</persName>, called <persName>Isaac Ha Kohen</persName>,<lb/> a
                righteous and pious man as you will<lb/> see in the newspaper of <persName>Rev
                    Isaac's</persName> of</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>last week. His son, <persName>Mr. Cohen</persName>, The<lb/> Parass of Rodaphei
                Zedek, asked me<lb/> to pronounce an appropriate eulogy<lb/> for his father, since I
                was a frequent<lb/> visitor to his house and a loyal<lb/> friend. I did as he told
                me and de-<lb/>cided to pronounce the eulogy in<lb/> his home after he had been
                prepared<lb/> for burial, because in that house he<lb/> used to sit and study for
                many years.<lb/> I uttered words that came from the<lb/> heart. Everyone wept for
                him and<lb/> every eye was moist with tears. But<lb/> I shall give you only a small
                portion<lb/> of it. I began with a quotation from<lb/> the Treatise
                    “Mored<add>?</add> Katan<add>?</add>”. (The<lb/> quotation from the eulogy takes
                up ½ <lb/> page. The point of it is that this old<lb/> man was very useful to the
                community<lb/> and was comparable to the sun at its<lb/> height. Hence this death is
                a universal<lb/> misfortune, comparable to the setting of<lb/> the sun at midday).
                The letter then continues:</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>But <persName>Rev. Issacs</persName> was evidently en-<lb/>vious for he did not
                mention my name<lb/> in his newspaper. He did mention all<lb/> the mourners, and who
                do you think<lb/> was at their head? <persName>Rev. Isaacs</persName>.<lb/> That is
                why I ask you to do me a favor<lb/> and mention my name in the “Occident”<lb/> and I
                shall compensate you whatever<lb/> you say for mentioning my name in a<lb/> good
                sense. Also send me The “Occident”<lb/> and I will consider it an act of <lb/>
                righteousness. Everyone here is angry<lb/> that he neglected to mention my
                name.<lb/> I shall be forever indebted to you and<lb/> I hope to do something in
                return. For<lb/> truth must stand forever.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I also should like to have you<lb/> let me know what you did with
                the<lb/> Sefer Torah in which the first chapter<lb/> of the portion “Mi-Ketz”
                (Genesis, 41) is<lb/> missing, and whether you corrected the<lb/> Sefer Torah. Has
                much correcting neces-</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>sary as you wrote in your letter<lb/> when I was in
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, and I<lb/> send greetings to my friend
                    <persName>Mrs. Papfer</persName>.<lb/> Now I want to tell you my good news
                that<lb/> my son in <placeName>Stalpe</placeName> in
                    <placeName>Pomerania</placeName> became<lb/> engaged and the wedding will be
                very<lb/> soon with Mazel Tov.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Again I ask you not to be<lb/> angry at me.</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">Eliezar Phillips</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">(Scribe in <placeName>N.Y.</placeName>)</p>
            <p>If you want to honor me with a<lb/> few lines my address is<lb/>
                <persName>L. Phillips</persName>, <placeName>203 Broome St., N.Y.</placeName></p>
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>
                <del>
                    <persName>MRS. SOLOMON GRAYZEL</persName>
                    <lb/>
                    <placeName>THE SHELBURNE<lb/> 13TH STREET AND LINDLEY AVENUE<lb/> PHILADELPHIA,
                        PA.</placeName>
                </del>
            </p>
